    "We found that 24.1% (2,169/8,995) of backbone genes, versus 13.4% (3,229/24,168) of cargo genes, encoded COG and Pfam functions with descriptions related to plasmid replication, transfer and maintenance (Supplementary Information).",
    "The most frequent type of function encoded on cargo genes was antibiotic resistance, including efflux pumps, which can provide general resistance to multiple antibiotics, and genes targeting specific classes of antibiotics, such as glycopeptides and β-lactams (Fig. 5a).",
